In NZ, a ton of our cyber security folks all worked from home - around 70%
I hear - and did so productively. The other side of the business - not so
much - but a bunch of technical types all managed to do software
development from home and loved it (lots of working on database and
productivity tools and collaborating with each other remotely).

Right now I work for the NZ Police (seconded for a year - up in October!).
I was tasked with setting up and running an open source team in Police
intel collections - and we've done that while also handling all the other
drama occurring here over the last 12 months. We were able to set up and
work from home quickly and efficiently, and Police accepted the small risks
involved. Arguably we're better set up now than before the pandemic - we're
back at the office but we have corporate and operational laptops and
accounts and we're able to work from home, or anywhere, at the drop of a
hat.

In fact, it seems to me like the open source contribution to the
all-of-government response and operations centres (a lot of unique alerting
was from my team, but others contributed sentiment and monitoring) was so
valued I'm seeing more interest from a range of agencies in setting up open
source cells in their organisations and there are some calls for people to
be collocated in a fusion centre even. Pretty hopeful I will be involved in
that!

Peter

