ing him to an earlier departure. He&#39;d negotiated with his manager to ha=
ve a later start time (he was a night owl and stayed up late to have more o=
verlap with West Pacific time zones) but wasn&#39;t able to take full advan=
tage of it because the agency didn&#39;t have enough parking so he ended up=
 spending 30+ minutes circling for an open spot. He thought the food in the=
 building sucked and felt very disconnected from his social network due to =
not being able to access social media software during the workday (this was=
 pre-smartphones, though those would have been stashed in a locker). Still,=
 he had a high mission-focus and a strong sense of patriotic duty, and I be=
lieve the agency could have retained him if he had been able to work from h=
ome two days a week. Given the above, he probably would have been more prod=
uctive and able to provide more-informed analysis.<br><br>The tech company =
I am now made an early decision to go full-remote during the pandemic, and =
has been able to make the transition fairly painlessly. They haven&#39;t co=
mmitted to full-remote as a permanent option yet, but they are now consider=
ing it as a hiring option (was off the table before), which will open up ou=
r talent recruiting pool. The CEO has noted that meetings seem to work best=
 if they are all-present or all-remote, but the mixed format tends to make =
it difficult to fully include the subset of participants who are remote. My=
 biggest hangup about working from home full-time has been the difficulty o=
f setting boundaries with the family. With the kids home from school and my=
 wife working remote as well, we&#39;ve had a hard time finding ways to all=
ow us both to be productive while not just parking the boys in front of a s=
creen. But I recognize that is more related to the phase of life than a uni=
versal constraint.</div><div><br></div><div>My prediction is that the intel=
 community will outlast this crisis and find a way to return to its familia=
r way of working but that the taste of something different will open the ey=
es of a portion of its workforce and that retention will be even worse than=
 usual for the next year or so.</div><div><br></div><div>As for working sec=
urely in a remote manner, I think the financial sector has shown this is po=
ssible for awhile now. Financial planners and wealth advisors work from the=
 road and have access to tens/hundreds of millions of dollars of portfolio =
net worth. Traders and quants often work remote and the deals and infrastru=
cture they have access to are valued in the billions. What the intel commun=
ity has not had to confront yet is a sustained challenge to its accustomed =
ways of working (though the extended field deployments of the War on Terror=
 came closer than anything) so it is blind to the cost of its current metho=
ds. The entertainment industry is in the midst of this revolution in distri=
buted working (how many games wouldn&#39;t get made if you couldn&#39;t out=
source to Ukraine or Poland for development &amp; art, how many animated se=
ries only came to be because of cheap artistic talent in East Asia, etc..) =
and companies that can&#39;t keep up will be beat by others (early example =
was Pixar essentially taking over Disney Animation). Entertainment companie=
s will find a way to push projects forward with a distributed model whilst =
